SM121 (DGX Spark GB10) shared memory fix for cutlass_moe_fp4 / nvfp4_blockwise_moe

Problem:
  Both SM120 (RTX 5090, RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell) and SM121 (DGX Spark GB10)
  provide only 99 KiB (101376 bytes) of shared memory per thread block.
  The 228 KiB figure that's often cited for "Blackwell" belongs to SM100
  (B200), not SM12x — per CUTLASS maintainer @depaulmillz in
  NVIDIA/cutlass#3144.

  CUTLASS's run_fp4_blockwise_scaled_group_mm_sm120() path in
  nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh uses `StageCountAutoCarveout` to pick the
  number of mainloop pipeline stages. Auto-carveout internally assumes
  the SM100 228 KiB budget and picks ~6 stages. With the default
  Pingpong schedule that duplicates mainloop buffers across two math
  warp groups, total SMEM requested becomes >100 KiB, 1+ KiB over the
  99 KiB device budget. The CUDA runtime then triggers a device-side
  assert inside the kernel launch path, which surfaces in userspace as
  a "device-side assert triggered" at nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh:78 (the
  next cudaMallocAsync sync-point on the stream, NOT the root cause
  line).

  Confirmed trigger on DGX Spark: any NVFP4 model (Qwen3-235B-A22B-NVFP4,
  GLM-4.7-NVFP4, Qwen3.5-397B-A17B-NVFP4, etc.) run with
  moe_runner_backend=triton or =cutlass under SGLang v0.5.10. The
  flashinfer_cutlass backend avoids this path entirely and works fine.

Fix:
  Two independent edits, both required.

  1. Override auto-carveout with an explicit StageCount<2>.
     StageCountAutoCarveout<sizeof(epilogue::SharedStorage)>
       -> StageCount<2>

     This is the *load-bearing* change that makes the total SMEM fit
     within 99 KiB. Mainloop SMEM scales linearly with the number of
     pipeline stages, so forcing 2 stages instead of the auto-picked 6
     cuts mainloop SMEM to roughly 1/3.

     2 is the minimum valid stage count for warp-specialized kernels:
     the producer warp TMAs into one stage while the consumer warp
     groups compute on the other. With StageCount<2> the pipeline is
     still double-buffered, we just get less producer-consumer overlap
     than at 6 stages. For NVFP4 GB10 where the bottleneck is SMEM not
     TMA bandwidth, this is acceptable.

     ThreadBlockShape is kept at <_128, _128, _128>. Earlier iterations
     of this patch tried halving N (Shape<_128, _64, _128>) and halving
     M (Shape<_64, _128, _128>) — BOTH failed CUTLASS template
     deduction at compile time. The Sm120 block-scaled CollectiveBuilder's
     SLayout atoms, MMA permutation (cute::C<128> baked in), and scale-
     factor TMA descriptors are all co-designed for a fixed 128x128x128
     tile; any deviation breaks TMA's "CTA_Tile and SLayout top-level
     size equivalence" static_assert at cute/atom/copy_traits_sm90_tma.hpp:744.
     Tile shrink is fundamentally incompatible with this pipeline.

  2. Ptr-array schedule Pingpong -> Cooperative.
     KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong ->
     KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative.

     Cooperative runs both math warp groups on the SAME output tile
     (split along M); they share mainloop buffers. Pingpong runs the
     groups on DIFFERENT tiles concurrently, which requires doubled
     peak SMEM for the concurrent buffering. Combined with hunk 1's
     stage reduction this gives a further ~2x cut of the effective
     per-block mainloop footprint.

     The Sm120 block-scaled CollectiveBuilder at
     cutlass/gemm/collective/builders/sm120_blockscaled_mma_builder.inl:72
     explicitly accepts BOTH Pingpong and Cooperative as valid tags for
     ArchTag=Sm120 + OpClassBlockScaledTensorOp, so Cooperative is a
     drop-in replacement — no other template parameter needs to change.

Previous iterations of this patch that did NOT work:
  - StageCount<1> alone: SFINAE reject (min 2 stages for warp-specialized)
  - KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecialized (no suffix): symbol does not exist
    in CUTLASS; only Pingpong/Cooperative variants are defined
  - Cooperative alone with default StageCountAutoCarveout: compiles,
    but runtime device-side assert at line 78 (SMEM still over budget
    because auto-carveout keeps picking ~6 stages under the wrong
    228 KiB budget assumption)
  - Cooperative + Shape<_128, _64, _128> (tile shrink in N): compile
    fails with "TMA requires CTA_Tile and SLayout top-level size
    equivalence" at line 744 — Sm120 blockscaled SLayout expects
    fixed N=128
  - Cooperative + Shape<_64, _128, _128> (tile shrink in M): same
    class of failure, the Sm120 blockscaled MMA permutation bakes
    in cute::C<128> for the M dimension

The final working combination is Cooperative + StageCount<2> at the
original <_128, _128, _128> tile shape.

  This follows the same general approach TensorRT-LLM merged in PR #12141
  (2026-03-18) for the analogous fp4_gemm_template.h path on SM121, though
  their fix operates on a different layer of the CUTLASS stack.

Refs:
  - https://github.com/NVIDIA/cutlass/issues/3144
      Root cause. Contains the verbatim SMEM numbers above
      (228 KiB SM100 vs 99 KiB SM120/121).
  - https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/pull/12141
      Reference fix from NVIDIA maintainers for the TRT-LLM FP4 GEMM path.
  - https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/pull/20012
      JIT migration: the target file moved from sgl-kernel/csrc/moe/
      to python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/.

Upstream source: sgl-project/sglang tag v0.5.10

--- a/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
+++ b/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
@@ -327,9 +327,17 @@
       ElementAccumulator,
       ThreadBlockShape,
       ClusterShape,
-      cutlass::gemm::collective::StageCountAutoCarveout<static_cast<int>(
-          sizeof(typename CollectiveEpilogue::SharedStorage))>,
-      cutlass::gemm::KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong>::CollectiveOp;
+      // dgxarley sgl-kernel-sm121.patch: force StageCount<2> instead of
+      // StageCountAutoCarveout. Auto-carveout internally assumes SM100's
+      // 228 KiB SMEM budget and picks ~6 stages, which on SM120/121 with
+      // only 99 KiB per block overflows by ~1 KiB. StageCount<2> is the
+      // minimum for warp-specialized (producer + consumer pipelining) and
+      // cuts mainloop SMEM by ~3x. See patch header + CUTLASS#3144.
+      cutlass::gemm::collective::StageCount<2>,
+      // Cooperative instead of Pingpong: both math warp groups share one
+      // tile + buffers (M-split), halving peak mainloop SMEM vs. Pingpong
+      // which runs groups on different tiles concurrently.
+      cutlass::gemm::KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative>::CollectiveOp;
 
   using GemmKernel = cutlass::gemm::kernel::GemmUniversal<ProblemShape, CollectiveMainloop, CollectiveEpilogue>;
 
